It appears that on a sufficient representation made to the Proctors by Masters of the University, the two Proctors‚ that is the officials who acted on behalf of the general body of superior graduates, were bound to bring lorward in the form os a statute the proposals made to them. The Masters and Doctors also elected the Bedels, who were at once the body-guard of the Chancellor, and were invested with important fonctions in the University. A smaller body, known early as the Con- gregation of the University and consisting of the younger Mastcrs, gave graces for degrees. The fact that this important function was conlerred on the junior members of the University is explained or justified on the ground that those who were nearest to their own exercises were the most competent persons to judge of the qualification of others. The election of the Proctors often ended in riot and bloodshed, 3ηά the graduates of the University were not only exceedingly tenacious os their privileges, but warmly resented any interference from bishop, abbot‚ or other spiri· tual authority, had a perpetual feud with the monks, and occasionally provoked some serious quarrels with the townsfolk.

Degrees were conferred in consideration of the success with which the candidate defended or impugned some thesis. The process was a kind of logical duel, in which one of the parties affirmed, the other denied a position. There was no limit to the subject of debate. Admitted principles of mental science, fundamental rules of moral conduct and duty, the highest verities in religion and church govemment, were open in these formal disputes to attack and defence.
